The paper deals with metric spaces and algorithms for constructing star-topology networks, which are topics commonly studied in the subfield of computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also involves solving the negative cycle detection problem, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and algorithms (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper discusses the concept of dilation, which is a measure of distortion in metric embeddings, and is a topic studied in both computational geometry and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The algorithmic techniques used in the paper involve solving linear programs and using binary search, which are common techniques in numerical analysis and optimization (cs.NA). Finally, the paper involves optimization and finding the minimum dilation, which is a topic studied in game theory and mechanism design (cs.GT).
